	<subsection>
		<title>Intoduction</title>
			<p>The key graphical properties of quadratic functions and parabolas were covered in <xref ref="list-properties-of-quadratic-functions-visual">List</xref>. If we don't have the graph of a quadratic function though, how do we know where these key features occur? In this section we'll explore how to algebraically determine where these features occur. We'll then use these processes to graph quadratic functions.</p>
<!--needs reference to an application-->
	</subsection>

	<subsection>
		<title>Direction of Parabolas</title>

		<p>As we've seen, parabolas can point either up or down. A simple example of an upward-pointing parabola is <m>y=x^2</m>, and a simple example of a downward pointing-parabola is <m>y=-x^2</m>:</p>

            <sidebyside widths="47% 47%" margins="0%">
				<figure xml:id="figure-basic-quadratic-function-up">
                <caption>Graph of <m>y=x^2</m></caption>
                    <image>
                        <description>a Cartesian grid with points (-3,9), (-2,4),(-1,1),(0,0),(1,1),(2,4),(3,9)</description>
                        <latex-image-code>
                            <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                                \begin{axis}[ymin=-10,ymax=10,xmin=-10,xmax=10,
                                            xtick={-8,-6,...,8},
                                            minor xtick={-10,-9,...,10},
                                            ytick={-8,-6,...,8},
                                            minor ytick={-10,-9,...,10}]
                                    \addplot+[domain=-3.16:3.16] {x^2};
                                    \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(-3,9)} ;
                                    \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(-2,4)} ;
                                    \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(-1,1)} ;
                                    \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(0,0)} ;
                                    \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(1,1)} ;
                                    \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(2,4)} ;
                                    \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(3,9)} ;
                                \end{axis}
                            \end{tikzpicture}
                            ]]>
                        </latex-image-code>
                    </image>
                </figure>

				<figure xml:id="figure-basic-quadratic-function-down">
                <caption>Graph of <m>y=-x^2</m></caption>
                    <image>
                        <description>a Cartesian grid with points (-3,-9), (-2,-4),(-1,-1),(0,0),(1,-1),(2,-4),(3,-9)</description>
                        <latex-image-code>
                            <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                                \begin{axis}[ymin=-10,ymax=10,xmin=-10,xmax=10,
                                            xtick={-8,-6,...,8},
                                            minor xtick={-10,-9,...,10},
                                            ytick={-8,-6,...,8},
                                            minor ytick={-10,-9,...,10}]
                                    \addplot+[domain=-3.16:3.16] {-1*x^2};
                                    \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(-3,-9)} ;
                                    \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(-2,-4)} ;
                                    \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(-1,-1)} ;
                                    \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(0,0)} ;
                                    \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(1,-1)} ;
                                    \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(2,-4)} ;
                                    \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(3,-9)} ;
                                \end{axis}
                            \end{tikzpicture}
                            ]]>
                        </latex-image-code>
                    </image>
                </figure>
            </sidebyside>

	<fact><p>The leading coefficient on a quadratic function determines whether the graph of this function points up or down.</p></fact>

	<p>To see why the leading coefficient of a parabola makes it point up or down, let's look numerically at values of the quadratic functions <m>y=-x^2+2x+3</m> and <m>y=x^2+2x+3</m>:</p>

