	<subsection>
		<title>Algebraically Determining the Vertex</title>

		<p>The vertex of a quadratic function is either the minimum point or the maximum point on its graph, depending on whether this function points up or down. When there are two horizontal intercepts for a quadratic function, we can see that the vertex occurs half-way between those two points. Similarly, when there is exactly one horizontal intercept, we know that this point is where the vertex occurs.</p>

            <sidebyside widths="47% 47%" margins="0%">
				<figure xml:id="figure-quadratic-function-two-horizontal-intercepts">
                <caption>Graph of <m>y=x^2+x-6</m></caption>
                    <image>
                        <description></description>
                        <latex-image-code>
                            <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                                \begin{axis}[]
                                    \addplot+[domain=-4.14:3.14] {(x-2)*(x+3)};
                                    \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(-3,0)} ;
                                    \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(2,0)} ;
                                \end{axis}
                            \end{tikzpicture}
                            ]]>
                        </latex-image-code>
                    </image>
                </figure>

				<figure xml:id="figure-quadratic-one-horizontal-intercept">
                <caption>Graph of <m>y=-(x-1)^2</m></caption>
                    <image>
                        <description></description>
                        <latex-image-code>
                            <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                                \begin{axis}[]
                                    \addplot+[domain=-4.646:0.646] {-1*(x+2)^2};
                                    \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(-2,0)} ;
                                \end{axis}
                            \end{tikzpicture}
                            ]]>
                        </latex-image-code>
                    </image>
                </figure>
            </sidebyside>

		<p>This visual method is quick, but it can only be used in limited cases.</p>

		<fact><p>The vertex of a quadratic function <m>f(x)=ax^2+bx+c</m> occurs where <m>x=-\frac{b}{2a}</m>, or at the point <m>\left(-\frac{b}{2a},f\left(-\frac{b}{2a}\right)\right)</m>.</p></fact>

		<p>This formula at first seems a bit random, but is actually related to the quadratic formula. Still thinking about the vertex occuring in the middle of two horizontal intercepts, we can see that this value is in the middle of the two values obtained from the quadratic formula:
			<me>x=\frac{{}\highlight{-b}{}\pm \lowlight{\sqrt{b^2-4ac}}}{{}\highlight{2a}{}}</me>
		</p>

